Most teams default to managed cloud services without questioning whether they actually need them. For some projects, that's the right call. But if your product requires full control over data location, infrastructure behavior, or compliance posture, self-hosting gives you that control. Appwrite was built with self-hosting as a first-class option, not an afterthought.

This guide covers why self-hosting matters, how to set up Appwrite on your own infrastructure, and what you need to get right before going to production.

# Why self-host Appwrite

Self-hosting is not about avoiding costs. It's about control. Here are the reasons that actually matter:

- **Data sovereignty.** Your data stays on infrastructure you own. This is a hard requirement for regulated industries and some government contracts.
- **Compliance flexibility.** You configure Appwrite to meet your specific compliance needs, whether that's GDPR, HIPAA, or SOC 2, instead of relying on a provider's posture.
- **Full customization.** Appwrite is open source. You can modify the source code, adjust internal configurations, and integrate with internal tooling that a managed service would never support.
- **Infrastructure choice.** Run Appwrite on AWS, DigitalOcean, bare metal, or your office server. You pick the hosting that fits your budget and latency requirements.

The trade-off is straightforward: you take on the operational burden of maintaining and scaling the instance yourself. If your team lacks DevOps experience or you're building an MVP, [Appwrite Cloud](https://cloud.appwrite.io/) is the faster path.

# What you need before installing

Appwrite runs on any operating system that supports [Docker CLI](https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop). Before you start, make sure your server meets these minimum requirements:

- **2 CPU cores**
- **4GB of RAM**
- **2GB of swap memory**
- **Docker Compose Version 2**

These minimums work for development and light workloads. For production, plan for more capacity based on your expected traffic and data volume.

# Installing Appwrite with Docker

Appwrite provides an automated Docker installer that walks you through the setup. Run this command on macOS or Linux:

```bash
docker run -it --rm \
    --volume /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock \
    --volume "$(pwd)"/appwrite:/usr/src/code/appwrite:rw \
    --entrypoint="install" \
    appwrite/appwrite:1.8.1
```

The installer prompts you to configure your HTTP/HTTPS ports, a secret encryption key, and your hostname. Once installation completes, open your server's hostname or IP address in a browser, create your first account, and set up a project.

If you prefer more control over the setup, you can use [manual installation](/docs/advanced/self-hosting/installation) with Docker Compose by downloading the `docker-compose.yml` and `.env` files directly.

For managed deployment without manual Docker configuration, Appwrite also offers [one-click deployments](/docs/advanced/self-hosting) on DigitalOcean, AWS Marketplace, Akamai, and Gitpod.

# Securing your instance for production

The default Appwrite setup is designed for quick starts, not production. Before exposing your instance to real traffic, address these areas:

**Set your encryption key.** Appwrite uses the `_APP_OPENSSL_KEY_V1` environment variable to encrypt sensitive data like API keys and webhook passwords. Set this immediately after installation and store it securely. Changing this key later means losing access to all previously encrypted data.

**Enforce HTTPS.** Always use HTTPS in production. You can force this with the `_APP_OPTIONS_FORCE_HTTPS` environment variable. Appwrite generates TLS certificates automatically using your configured hostname.

**Restrict console access.** By default, only the first user who signs up can access the Appwrite Console. For additional security, use `_APP_CONSOLE_WHITELIST_IPS` or `_APP_CONSOLE_WHITELIST_EMAILS` to limit who can reach your dashboard. The [security documentation](/docs/advanced/self-hosting/production/security) covers these options in detail.

**Configure email delivery.** Set up an SMTP provider so Appwrite can send verification emails, password resets, and team invitations. Without this, your users won't be able to recover accounts or verify their email addresses. See the [email configuration guide](/docs/advanced/self-hosting/configuration/email) for supported providers.

# Scaling a self-hosted Appwrite instance

Appwrite's architecture separates stateless and stateful containers. The API, Realtime, and Executor containers are stateless, so you can replicate them behind a load balancer to handle more traffic.

The stateful components, MariaDB and Redis, require a different approach. MariaDB handles persistent storage while Redis manages caching, queues, and pub/sub messaging. To scale these, set up standard database clusters the same way you would for any application using these technologies.

You can tune worker performance by adjusting the `_APP_WORKER_PER_CORE` environment variable, which controls the number of worker processes per CPU core. The default is 6, but your optimal value depends on your hardware and workload. The [scaling documentation](/docs/advanced/self-hosting/production/scaling) covers this in more detail.

# Backing up your Appwrite data

Self-hosted instances require you to implement your own backup strategy. Appwrite stores data across several components:

- **Database (MariaDB)** for user data, documents, and configuration
- **Docker volumes** for uploaded files, function code, build artifacts, and SSL certificates
- **Environment variables** in your `.env` file, including the critical `_APP_OPENSSL_KEY_V1` encryption key

For database backups, use `mysqldump` to create logical backups. For storage volumes, shut down Appwrite before backing up to avoid data inconsistency.

Follow the **3-2-1 rule**: keep 3 copies of your data, on 2 different media types, with 1 stored offsite. Schedule automated backups with cron jobs and test your restores quarterly. The [backup documentation](/docs/advanced/self-hosting/production/backups) covers the full procedure including commands for volume backup and restore.

# Self-hosting vs Appwrite Cloud

Choosing between self-hosting and Appwrite Cloud depends on your team's priorities:

| Aspect | Appwrite Cloud | Self-hosting |
|--------|---------------|--------------|
| **Setup** | Zero configuration | Manual Docker setup |
| **Maintenance** | Fully managed updates and scaling | You handle updates, scaling, and patches |
| **Data control** | Managed infrastructure | Full control over data location |
| **Compliance** | Built-in compliance | Configure to meet your specific requirements |
| **Scaling** | Automatic | Manual configuration |
| **Customization** | Limited to available settings | Full access to source code and configuration |
| **Cost model** | Predictable subscription pricing | Infrastructure costs you manage directly |

Self-hosting makes sense when data sovereignty, regulatory compliance, or deep customization are non-negotiable. Appwrite Cloud is the better choice when you want to ship fast without managing infrastructure, especially if your team is small or lacks dedicated DevOps capacity.

Appwrite Cloud and self-hosted Appwrite use the same API/SDK model within supported versions, and you can migrate from Cloud to self-hosting later if your requirements change. Cloud receives new features first, so exact parity depends on the self-hosted version you're running.

